Stokes, 1887
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1436,965,1206]" pageId="10" pageNumber="425">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,524,965,990]" pageId="10" pageNumber="425">Record on hydrachnid mites:</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation box="[540,736,965,990]" pageId="10" pageNumber="425" refId="ref11740" refString="Ramadan, S. A. (2004) Description of epibiont ciliates on the water mite Unionicola tetrafurcatus and their disdribution on the host legs. Egyptian journal of Zoology, e 42, 97 - 112." type="journal article">Ramadan (2004)</bibRefCitation>
reported 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stokes" authorityYear="1887" box="[859,1104,965,990]" class="Oligohymenophorea" family="Epistylididae" genus="Rhabdostyla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Peritrichida" pageId="10" pageNumber="425" phylum="Ciliophora" rank="species" species="vernalis">
<emphasis box="[859,1104,965,990]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="425">Rhabdostyla vernalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
on adult mites 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ramadan &amp; Aboul-Dahab" authorityYear="2002" class="Arachnida" family="Unionicolidae" genus="Unionicola" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="10" pageNumber="425" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tetrafurcatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="425">Unionicola tetrafurcatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
associated with mussel 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cailliaud" authorityYear="1827" box="[572,817,1001,1026]" class="Gastropoda" family="Barleeiidae" genus="Caelatura" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="10" pageNumber="425" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="aegyptiaca">
<emphasis box="[572,817,1001,1026]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="425">Caelatura aegyptiaca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
collected from a site on the eastern bank of the River Nile, north of Sohag University Campus, Egypt. The highest mean density of ciliates was recorded on the fourth leg of the mite and declined gradually towards the first leg, which recorded the lowest mean number and attached to the bases of the setae on the legs of the mite (
<bibRefCitation box="[687,863,1109,1134]" pageId="10" pageNumber="425" refId="ref11740" refString="Ramadan, S. A. (2004) Description of epibiont ciliates on the water mite Unionicola tetrafurcatus and their disdribution on the host legs. Egyptian journal of Zoology, e 42, 97 - 112." type="journal article">Ramadan 2004</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="425" type="description">
